## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — no longer needed since abort can't happen.
3. **`default(T)` for non-nullable reference types** — with NRTs enabled, `default` is `null` and may warn.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Blocks the caller just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to match original throw behavior.
            throw ae.InnerExceptions[0];
        }

        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async overload — preferred in modern code.
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Differences

| Aspect | .NET Framework (old) | .NET 8 (new) |
|---|---|---|
| Cancellation | `Thread.Abort()` — rude, non-cooperative | `CancellationToken` — cooperative |
| Work signature | `Func<T>` | `Func<CancellationToken, T>` |
| Execution | Raw `Thread` | `Task.Run` on thread pool |
| Abort handler | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Not needed — removed entirely |

### Pitfalls

1. **Cooperative cancellation requires callee participation.** If `work` ignores the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. There is no safe equivalent to `Thread.Abort()` — this is by design.

2. **Truly uncooperative code** — if you must kill runaway work that you can't modify (e.g., third-party library), isolate it in a **separate process** and kill the process on timeout:
   ```csharp
   // Nuclear option — only for code you cannot modify
   var proc = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
   if (!proc.WaitForExit(timeout))
   {
       proc.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
       throw new TimeoutException("...");
   }
   ```

3. **`Task.Result` vs `await`** — the sync overload blocks via `.Wait()` / `.Result`, which can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer the async overload.

4. **Exception wrapping changed** — `Task.Wait()` wraps in `AggregateException`; the migrated code unwraps single exceptions to preserve original behavior.

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (legacy callers)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check periodically
        // ... do work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async (preferred)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```
